as a mountain in the southern hemisphere, others such as Marie de France told of The Legend of the Purgatory of Saint Patrick, in which the entrance was on Station Island in County Donegal. This idea of purification by fire had appalled the Eastern Orthodox Church and was one of the factors in the split from Rome in 1054, but flourished in the West up to the reformations of C16th when it was again particularly divisive.\n\nWith\n\nLaura Ashe\nAssociate Professor of English and fellow of Worcester College at the University of Oxford\n\nMatthew Treherne\nProfessor of Italian Literature at the University of Leeds\n\nand\n\nHelen Foxhall Forbes\nAssociate Professor of Early Medieval History at Durham University\n\nProducer: Simon Tillotson."},"image_url":"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/images/ic/{recipe}/p0538jhg.jpg","duration":{"value":2918,"label":"48 mins"},"progress":null,"availability":{"from":"2017-05-25T10:33:46Z","to":null,"label":"Available for over a year"},"container":{"type":"brand","id":"b006qykl","urn":"urn:bbc:radio:brand:b006qykl","title":"In Our Time","synopses":{"short":"Melvyn Bragg and guests discuss the ideas, people and events that have shaped our world.","medium":"Melvyn Bragg and guests discuss the ideas, people and events that have shaped our world.","long":null},"activities":[]},"uris":[{"type":"latest","id":null,"label":"Latest","uri":"/v2/programmes/playable?container=b006qykl&sort=sequential&type=episode&experience=domestic"}],"activities":[],"play_context":null,"guidance":{"competition_warning":false,"warnings":null},"recommendation":null},{"id":"p054ldzq","type":"playable_item","urn":"urn:bbc:radio:episode:b08rp369","network":{"id":"bbc_radio_four","key":"radio4","short_title":"Radio 4","logo_url":"https://sounds.files.bbci.co.uk/3.5.0/networks/bbc_radio_four/{type}_{size}.{format}","network_type":"master_brand"},"release":{"date":"2017-06-01T00:00:00Z","label":"01 Jun 2017"},"titles":{"primary":"In Our Time","secondary":"Enzymes","tertiary":null,"entity_title":"Enzymes"},"synopses":{"short":"Melvyn Bragg and guests discuss enzymes, the catalysts essential for life.","medium":"Melvyn Bragg and guests discuss enzymes, the proteins that control the speed of chemical reactions in organisms which would otherwise happen too slowly to keep the organisms alive.","long":"Melvyn Bragg and guests discuss enzymes, the proteins that control the speed of chemical reactions in living organisms. Without enzymes, these reactions would take place too slowly to keep organisms alive: with their actions as catalysts, changes which might otherwise take millions of years can happen hundreds of times a second. Some enzymes break down large molecules into smaller ones, like the ones in human intestines, while others use small molecules to build up larger, complex ones, such as those that make DNA. Enzymes also help keep cell growth under control, by regulating the time for cells to live and their time to die, and provide a way for cells to communicate with each other. \n\nWith \n\nNigel Richards\nProfessor of Biological Chemistry at Cardiff University\n\nSarah Barry\nLecturer in Chemical Biology at King's College London\n\nAnd \n\nJim Naismith\nDirector of the Research Complex at Harwell\nBishop Wardlaw Professor of Chemical Biology at the University of St Andrews\nProfessor of Structural Biology at the University of Oxford\n\nProducer: Simon Tillotson."},"image_url":"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/images/ic/{recipe}/p053xwz3.jpg","duration":{"value":2916,"label":"48 mins"},"progress":null,"availability":{"from":"2017-06-01T09:57:30Z","to":null,"label":"Available for over a year"},"container":{"type":"brand","id":"b006qykl","urn":"urn:bbc:radio:brand:b006qykl","title":"In Our Time","synopses":{"short":"Melvyn Bragg and guests discuss the ideas, people and events that have shaped our world.","medium":"Melvyn Bragg and guests discuss the ideas, people and events that have shaped our world.","long":null},"activities":[]},"uris":[{"type":